Answer: You seem to be hitting a limitation of the TeX engine.  The `\newcommand` which defines the `\textgreek` command does not get run at the time the `\textgreek` macro is run.  I believe this is because the `\newcommand` is run when the `\begin{document}` runs.  You can verify this by putting in a `\renewcommand{\textgreek}[1]{{\text{\texttt{\ensuremath{\mathrm{#1}}}}}}` and it will compile.

The problem is that the line has a lot of characters on it so the engine runs out of memory and dies.  The `\renewcommand` is needed because `\newcommand` doesn't run again when you redefine a macro.  You could probably add a `\newline` or `\chardef` between the `\newcommand` and `\textgreek` so that they are on a different line.  However, as the error message said, this will probably not work because you won't be able to put `\left` and `\right` on the same line.

\strong{EDIT:}

Here is the `\newcommand` definition of the `\textgreek` macro:

\begin{code}
\newcommand{\textgreek}[1]{\texttt{\ensuremath{\mathrm{#1}}}}
\end{code}

Notice the `\texttt`.  This causes a problem because `\\texttt` does not work as a command name in TeX.  This is because `\\texttt` is a command to produce a macro that takes a macro argument (in this case `\texttt` that is used to get an output of `\text`.  This means the `\texttt` argument is ignored by the macro and it gets expanded to the `\texttt{\ensuremath{#1}}` as the macro's argument.

To avoid the problem, the `\newcommand` macro should look like:

\begin{code}
\newcommand{\textgreek}[1]{{\text{\texttt{\ensuremath{\mathrm{#1}}}}}}
\end{code}

With this definition, TeX will not get confused with `\\texttt` and the command will work.

\strong{EDIT 2:}

I have updated my answer to show how to use `\textgreek` and `\texttt` in your MWE.  I have also added an example using the `\renewcommand` technique.

Here is a simple MWE with your code and the `\renewcommand` trick:

\begin{code}
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{etoolbox}

\newcommand{\textgreek}[1]{{\text{\texttt{\ensuremath{\mathrm{#1}}}}}}

\begin{document}

\textgreek{δὲ}

\end{document}
\end{code}

You can see the `\\texttt` has worked as `\texttt` is now defined as `\text{\texttt{\ensuremath{#1}}}` (assuming your document is using the Latin font of course)

You can also do it with `\renewcommand`:

\begin{code}
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{etoolbox}

\renewcommand{\textgreek}[1]{{\text{\texttt{\ensuremath{\mathrm{#1}}}}}}

\begin{document}

\textgreek{δὲ}

\end{document}
\end{code}

